<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-632-221  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 632 221.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Nov 19 1990 n617 p52(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>First things first. (learning a programming language) (SourceCode) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Weiss, Ray.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There are two stages in learning a programming language:understanding the concepts, structure and primary operators of thelanguage; and learning enough secondary operations to createefficient, workable code.andP;  A piecemeal approach to learninglanguages and systems is recommended: introduce the core first,followed by presentations of secondaries in stages of increasedcomplexity.andP;  Ease of learning and good design may not be enough.andO;It is important to know the practical limits and costs of using asoftware system or tool.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Programming InstructionProgramming LanguagesSource CodeProgram Development Techniques.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>